  "text": "Now we use the integral formulas of n [CITATION_1] and n (0) to express the functions m 1 and m 2 in terms of the entries of Ψ (0) (ζ; σ) which are defined in Section 1.1. First we consider n (0) . By the definition given by (1.36)-(1.41) , we have that each component of n (0) (z) is expressed by a sum of integrals on Γ [CITATION_2] where the functions f (ζ; 2 2/3 (2s − τ 2 )) and g(ζ; 2 2/3 (2s − τ 2 )) the contour Σ tac are defined in equation (1.72) and in Figure 7 , respectively. By the same argument, we have that m 3 (z; s, τ ) and m 4 (z; s, τ ) have similar but slightly more complicated formulas as integrals on Σ tac . Here we note that the contour Σ tac can be replaced by Σ 2MM where the definition for f and g is still given by (1.72).",
